04808nam a22006255i 9781442670211DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182002onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426702117 a10.3138/97814426702112doi  a(DE-B1597)497121  a(OCoLC)1078907412  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a343.71507/692/0899731 aWicken, William C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMi'kmaq Treaties on Trial :bHistory, Land, and Donald Marshall Junior /cWilliam C. Wicken. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE The Mi'kmaq in 1726 -- t25 November 1993, Halifax, Nova Scotia -- tChapter One. The Mi'kmaq and Land -- tChapter Two. The Mi'kmaq Polity -- tPART TWO: The 1726 Treaty -- tArticle of Peace and Agreement: Annapolis Royal 1726 -- tReciprocal Promises Made by Captain John Doucett: 1726 -- t21 November 1994, Antigonish, Nova Scotia -- tChapter Three. The Genesis of the 1726 Treaty: The Wabanaki-New England War of 1722-1725 -- tChapter Four. The Languages of Communication -- tChapter Five. The 1726 Treaty and Utrecht -- tChapter Six. Establishing Laws, Establishing Relationships -- tChapter Seven. British Politics and Treaty Making -- tPART THREE: Renewing the 1726 Treaty -- tTreaty of Peace and Friendship -- tFebruary 1996, Halifax, Nova Scotia -- tChapter Eight. The Founding of Halifax: Re-interpreting the 1726 Treaty -- tChapter Nine. The 1760-1761 Treaties -- tPART FOUR: The 1726 Treaty in History and Law -- t27 June 1996, Antigonish, Nova Scotia -- tConclusion -- tSeptember to November 1999 -- tGlossary of Names -- tGlossary of Places -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1725-6 the British colonial government of Nova Scotia signed a treaty of friendship and peace with the local Mi'kmaq people. This treaty explicitly acknowledged the co-existence of Mi'kmaq and British law - but much of its meaning stemmed from its complex negotiation, which was influenced by the history of aboriginal-European relations in Acadia prior to 1726. William Wicken argues that after 1749 a more forceful British military presence led officials to re-interpret the treaty in the light of its own interests.From 1994 to 1996, the author was an expert witness for the defence at the Marshall trial, during which the Supreme Court of Canada integrated aboriginal perspectives on treaty-making into current interpretations. Dr Wicken was one of the historians who gathered and presented the historical evidence to the court. This timely and original work intersperses close analysis of the 1726 treaty with discussions of the Marshall case, and shows how the inter-cultural relationships and power dynamics of the past, have shaped both the law and the social climate of the present. The author argues that the treaties must be viewed in their historical context, and that of the oral tradition of Mi'kmaq people, to be properly understood.Current high-profile legal cases involving aboriginal rights lend this work a special significance among the legal and academic communities, where it is destined to spark debate. It is of particular relevance to history and native studies students.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267021140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442670211423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442670211.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACK